Noah lived in an evil world but had no desire to make its inhabitants his close friends.
He did not seek the companionship of ungodly people.
He and the seven members of his family occupied themselves with the doing of God-given work, which included building an ark.
Meanwhile, Noah was also a preacher of righteousness.
Noah’s preaching, his work on the ark, and his association with his family kept him busy doing good things that pleased God.
As a result, Noah and his immediate family survived the Flood.
We should be grateful to them because all of us today are the descendants of those who served Jehovah—faithful Noah, Noah’s wife, his sons, and their wives.
Similarly, loyal and obedient first-century Christians kept themselves separate from ungodly people and survived the destruction of Jerusalem and the Jewish system of things in 70 C.
